From: gwr@mc.com (Gordon W. Ross)
Crossposted-To: comp.lang.perl,comp.lang.tcl
Subject: Re: CFC/CFI: XSysadmin
Date: 5 Oct 1993 00:56:29 GMT
Reply-To: gwr@mc.com

In article <28ptvm$b93@peanuts.informatik.uni-tuebingen.de>
will@oliver (Michael Will) writes:

> CFC / CFI     Call for Code / Call for Ideas :-)
> Xsysadmin - this is what I want to write, only I think there already is
> a lot of code outside? 
>
> Please contact me if you are working on something similar, have done
> something alike or [...]
> 
> I would like to make a LinuxConfigurationtool for
[ accounts, uucp, smail, cnews/tin, networking, cron, printers, etc. ]
> 
> I do not know whether it is a good idea to put this all into one program,
> especially since many people should contribute to this program - I cannot
> do it all alone. 

Here are some ideas for you:

(1) Use separate programs (or data files) for generating the user screens
    to allow add-on packages to add new screens, and simplify debugging.

(2) Realize the screens using an interpreter, to make it easy to add
    new data files (or fix buggy ones), but be careful to implement
    the interpreter efficiently to minimize user-visible delays.

(3) Provide both an X and text implementation of the interpreter.
    (The interpreter would be useful even if X is not available.)

(4) Design a language for the interpreter that:
(4a)  Can be interpreted efficiently
(4b)  Uses a declarative form to describe screens
(4c)  Lets screen fields have "input rules" and "actions"
(4d)  Allows an action to affect other fields by name
(4e)  Simplifies use of existing tools as part of an "action"
        (i.e. can run a shell command and save its exit status)

These ideas may sound similar to USL's "System Administration Package"
(sysadm) because sysadm uses data files interpreted by the "Form and
Menu Language Interpreter" (FMLI).  Note, however, that FMLI fails
in areas 4a, 4d, 4e, and is generally just a slow implementation.
The FMLI language design makes it difficult to express: the intended
evaluation time of each component, the appropriate substitution and
quoting of temporary strings, and changes to other screen components.

The design of the screen description language is central to the
success of any interpreted user interface like this.  There will be
many forms and menus to write, so the language needs to be expressive
enough to make the job easy for the authors of all those screens.

My experience has been that a declarative form is good for describing
the overall contents of a form or menu, and a procedural form is good
for describing the actions associated with the various events that can
happen to a field (selection, modification, enter, exit).

There are two languages I can think of that one might use as a
basis for designing the screen description language (SDL):  

Lisp:   Has several advantages, but is unfamiliar to most people.
        It is easily interpreted, and can easily be used for
        either declarative or procedural forms of expression.

Tcl/Tk: I am not very familiar with Tcl or Tk though I gather they
        are interpreted procedural languages.  I have doubts about
        how effectively these could be used for declarative form.

Perl:   Same problems as Tcl, I guess.

Does anyone else have experience with interpreted languages for
screen/form/menu description?  What has worked well for you?

--
Gordon W. Ross                  Mercury Computer Systems
gwr@mc.com                      199 Riverneck Road
508-256-1300                    Chelmsford, MA 01824-2820

